### Audit rules of engagement

- **Do not apply any fix during an audit.** The audit produces a report only. The user decides what to fix and when.
- **Confirm dead code before listing it.** Run a search/grep for every symbol before calling it dead. A false-positive dead-code finding in an audit report wastes developer time and erodes trust.
- **Systemic patterns outrank individual findings.** If the same issue appears in 8 files, report it once as a pattern with representative examples — not as 8 separate findings.
- **Do not pad the report.** An audit with 3 real BLOCKERs and 10 real SHOULD-FIXes is better than one inflated with NIT-level findings to look thorough. Empty sections are correct output.
- **Traverse completely before reporting.** Do not emit partial results mid-traversal unless the user explicitly asks for incremental output. A half-finished audit report is worse than no report — it creates a false sense that unscanned layers are clean.
- **Flag scope limitations explicitly.** If a layer could not be fully analyzed (file too large, no read access, generated code with no source), state that in the report header so the user knows the audit boundary.